"{\n  \"CODA\": {\n    \"text\": \"CODA\\nCLOSE\\nPowered By The Human Phenotype Project\\nTHE WORLD’S LARGEST CONTROLLED MULTI-OMICS AND DEEPLY PHENOTYPED DATA LIBRARY AND BIOBANK\\nOur CODA discovery engine uses AI, machine learning, and advanced bioinformatics to generate human-first, targeted, and effective precision probiotics with applications from infancy through aging. \\nCODA is powered by the Human Phenotype Project, the world's richest host-microbiome data set, emerging from the lab of Prof. Eran Segal, Ph.D. Through this extensive dataset, CODA deciphers new microbiome-derived biomarkers linked to a range of health conditions, highlighting the intricate relationship between the microbiome and human health.\\nCODA's advanced analytics enable a deep dive into the complex interactions that influence health trajectories, allowing for the design of interventions that support health and well-being across lifespan. Based on a deep longitudinal data set of tens of thousands of subjects, CODA also optimizes clinical trial processes, including design, enrollment, implementation, and longitudinal follow-up.\\nCollaborators\\nERAN SEGAL, PH.D.\\nTHE WEIZMANN INSTITUTE OF SCIENCE\\nData\\n40,000+ subject years of data and 3,000,000+ unique data points \\n10,000+ sets of stool and oral microbiome data coupled with host genetic analysis \\n11K+ subjects; tracking to 100K+ people in the next five years across multiple countries\\nMethodology\\nU\",\n    \"imgs\": [\n      \"https://images.ctfassets.net/oq6r31hkrb9r/73Wnrh77Lwb5XN2d8Qgqru/fc8a6456330f79d0f55426dc581c1251/image_7202086.jpg\",\n      \"https://images.ctfassets.net/oq6r31hkrb9r/jl6Lwuxb03j3bqDmyY3p9/7c7e2569c24f8b2102c3961b71ee0e97/image_7202087.jpg\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"LUCA\": {\n    \"text\": \"LUCA\\nCLOSE\\nPowered By The LUCA Dataset\\nTHE MOST COMPREHENSIVE NON-REDUNDANT GENE CATALOG OF THE HUMAN VAGINAL MICROBIOME\\nOriginating from over 15 years of the Ravel Lab's vaginal microbiome research, our LUCA engine is driving a paradigm shift in women's health.\\nThe vaginal microbiome plays a critical role in reproductive, urogenital and gynecological health. Everyday factors can impact its balance, including hormonal changes, sexual activity, menstruation, contraception, lubricants, antibiotic usage, and lifestyle choices.\\nPropelled by the unmet needs, lived experiences, and data gaps in women’s health, we’ve leveraged almost two decades of vaginal microbiome sampling and metagenomic research to unlock the vast potential of this ecosystem. LUCA designs targeted microbial consortia to establish and maintain an optimal vaginal microbiome utilizing microbial genomics, an exclusive data set, and our proprietary vaginal strain bank of over 1,000 human samples.\\nWith LUCA, we are advancing both consumer health and therapeutic solutions to target a range of conditions and the greatest unmet needs in vaginal health –– from bacterial vaginosis and UTIs to HPV and menopausal challenges.\\nCollaborators\\nJACQUES RAVEL, PHD\\nTHE UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND SCHOOL OF MEDICINE\\nData\\n948,158 non-redundant genes \\n785,269 functionally annotated genes \\n431,653 bacterial genes \\n269 bacterial species  \\n10,9\",\n    \"imgs\": [\n      \"https://images.ctfassets.net/oq6r31hkrb9r/7hR4p6e78Jh3Ea74Rke6J7/b32e1b7b4dd3747076cadb4b7de7c8a1/Frame_415.jpg\",\n      \"https://images.ctfassets.net/oq6r31hkrb9r/3X4vW0EBhV4xwnpK3ZCLSM/8f6cc3491f065fca2b55cb2f625c922f/The_University_of_Maryland_School_of_Medicine.jpg\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"ALLO\": {\n    \"text\": \"ALLO\\nCLOSE\\nPowered By EDAPS-I\\nA PROPRIETARY IMMUNOLOGY PLATFORM TO SCREEN, EVALUATE, AND VALIDATE SUBSTANCES FOR DOSAGE, TOXICITY, AND RECOVERY OF EPITHELIAL BARRIERS AND THE MICROBIOME.\\nBuilding on nearly three decades of immunology research and over 520 peer-reviewed publications from Dr. Cezmi Akdis at the University of Zurich, our ALLO discovery engine operates at the interface between humans and their microbiome: the epithelial barriers. These barriers are the protective cellular layers lining the skin, respiratory tract, and gut, and are under continuous assault from many of the compounds found in everyday consumer products—including preservatives, emulsifiers, nanoparticles, and microplastics. These omnipresent compounds are known to affect these critical barriers, causing microbial dysbiosis and chronic ‘microinflammation.’ We are evolving our understanding of toxicity to move beyond “clean” and power a new standard of microbiome and barrier-safe topical applications.\\nThis engine combines host and microbial immunology to identify compounds that protect the microbiome and restore our epithelial barriers, in addition to the identification and isolation of keystone skin species that deliver dermatological benefits throughout life.\\nCollaborators\\nCEZMI A. AKDIS, MD\\nSWISS INSTITUTE OF ALLERGY AND ASTHMA RESEARCH (SIAF)\\nData\\n20 years of research \\n60+ scientific papers \\n200+ co\",\n    \"imgs\": [\n      \"https://images.ctfassets.net/oq6r31hkrb9r/jT9XBUD1QqKeXrQFmMh8b/68dcb81a397aeeb3319033c30238f590/Cezmi.jpg\",\n      \"https://images.ctfassets.net/oq6r31hkrb9r/3cBhMQjod4pHgTGk7gENNY/7f284ea7d26ab3f5c7396923f42314b3/image_7202084.jpg\"\n    ]\n  }\n}"